[Student "S"]
{You are thinking slam; your first step is a jump to 3\C.

Partner says 4\C;  

You are thinking slam; your first step is a jump to 3\C.

Partner says 4\C; 

With partner agreeing \Cs, one possibility would be for you to cue-bid your \HA. Another would be just to bid 6\C. You choose the second approach.

South plays 6\C. West leads the \H10. East plays low and you win the \HQ.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 1 : \C = 0 :: Total = 2

Your best chance at another winner is the \D suit. West MAY have both the \D K Q, if not you will have to establish the suit. 

At trick 2 pull just one round of trumps with the \CK. Then play a small \D, finessing the \DJ when West plays low. East takes the \DQ and returns the \SJ. 

Go up with your \SK, you may need the entry to dummy later. Pull one more trump with the \CQ, then play a small \D to dummy's \DA. Ruff a \D with a high trump, West discarding.  

Enter dummy with the \CA, pulling West's last trump as you do, and ruff one more \D, establishing the fifth \D. Enter dummy with the \SA and discard your losing \S on the good \D.

It is important to be careful with entries to the hand where you are trying to establish a suit.

If the suit splits evenly perhaps you can be a little sloppy and still get by.

But in cases like this one, with a 4-2 split, you cannot afford to waste an entry too early.}
[Play "W"]HT

